<tr><td class=3D"item_content" style=3D'border-collapse:collapse; color:#33=
3; display:block; font-family:Georgia, Times, "Times New Roman", "Hiragino =
Kaku Gothic Pro", "Meiryo", serif; font-size:15px; line-height:1.4'><div cl=
ass=3D"text_reset item_content with_margin_below" style=3D'color:#333; disp=
lay:block; font-family:Georgia, Times, "Times New Roman", "Hiragino Kaku Go=
thic Pro", "Meiryo", serif; font-size:15px; line-height:1.4'><div id=3D"Uln=
vBK"><div class=3D"truncated_para_breaks expanded_q_text TruncatedAnswerFor=
NewAnswerEmail TruncatedAnswer TruncatedAnswerForEmail TruncatedQText" id=
=3D"__w2_vMl4I7i_truncated"><span class=3D"rendered_qtext" style=3D"color:#=
333"><p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; m=
argin-bottom:1em">It is said that the pilots of the US air force after the =
Korean war massively passed training, during which they were trained to res=
ist the psychological effects of the enemy. It is also said that psychologi=
cal torture is much more effective than physical torture: the human psyche =
recovers from such an impact for a long time... And they say that the CIA h=
as developed a whole system of"non-human impact". These are just some examp=
les from the"torture Report".</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">The intelligence Committee of the us Senate in 2014 published =
a shortened version of its study on the use of torture in the CIA. The publ=
ic document contains 528 pages describing CIA "enhanced interrogation techn=
iques".</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Methods of psychological and physical impact on prisoners were=
 developed by psychologists who previously collaborated with the school of =
survival in emergency conditions of the US air force.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">According to the human rights research Center of the Americas,=
 psychological torture should meet the following four criteria:</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">1. Suffering;</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">2. Punishment;</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">3. Duration;</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">4. The absence of direct physical violence.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Lack of sleep</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Lack of sleep us state Department, torture, us, CIA</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Sleep deprivation is a form of torture where a prisoner is dep=
rived of sleep for a long time. Sleep is vital for humans and animals. It i=
s not yet clear how long a person can stay awake. Today, the set record bel=
ongs to Randy Gardner, who was awake for 264.4 hours without the use of sti=
mulants.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Methods, depriving of sleep, play loud blasting music, bright =
strobe lights, and the placement of man on step of the podium, from which, =
falling, he receives an electric shock... After a certain period of time wi=
thout sleep, hallucinations begin. If the lack of sleep becomes permanent f=
or several months, it leads to mental illness.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Other, lighter, consequences may include deterioration of emot=
ional state. David Dinges, Professor of psychology and Director of experime=
ntal psychiatry at the University of Pennsylvania, argues that "when a pers=
on is deprived of sleep, he ceases to experience positive emotions. He may =
claim to be happy =E2=80=94 but he doesn't really experience anything."</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Ostracism</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Ostracism, the U.S. state Department, torture, United States, =
CIA</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Social stigma is a form of psychological torture, which is roo=
ted in the Middle ages. Do you remember the term "pillory"? Here we are: th=
e first mention of this beautiful device dates back to 1274. So this tortur=
e has a long history.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Shameful pole with holes for the head and hands of the man was=
 installed in the most crowded place: in the shopping area or at the town h=
all. It allowed to humiliate the guilty, to scold him, to throw stones at h=
im and even sometimes to beat.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">An interesting case occurred in 1703, when Danielle Defo was s=
entenced to a "pillory" for libel. However, public opinion of him as a hero=
 was so high that he was thrown flowers, not dirt or excrement.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">15 most sophisticated psychological torture of the us state De=
partment, torture, us, CIA</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">At a time when Saddam Hussein was in power, one of the most fa=
mous prisons in the world was Abu Ghraib. After Hussein was overthrown, it =
housed the us military prison. It turned out that the us army mocked the ca=
ptive Iraqis. A nationwide scandal broke out and eleven soldiers were convi=
cted of crimes.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">One of the forms of torture used in Abu Ghraib was forced nudi=
ty. Male prisoners were forcibly stripped naked and forced to stand in fron=
t of others in which the mother gave birth.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">In Arab culture, nudity and nudity in front of others are humi=
liating for men.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Insulation</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">The isolation of the US state Department, torture, United Stat=
es, CIA</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">One of the favorite methods of psychological pressure is the l=
ong-term isolation of the prisoner. A former prisoner, Gairat Bahir, recall=
ed:</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">- If you don't cooperate, they lock you in a box as long as th=
e coffin, where there is no oxygen. No light. You feel like you're being bu=
ried alive.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Isolation or solitary confinement is used in some US prisons.<=
/p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">What are the consequences of such a conclusion for a person? I=
n the infamous 'pit of despair' experience of the macaques, conducted in th=
e 1950s, psychologist Harry Harlow found that in a day or two the animals '=
 became deeply restless, indifferent, or anxious. Roamed the cage, cripplin=
g themselves or swaying madly from side to side, not responding."</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Sound</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Sound torture is used to influence prisoners with loud music o=
r white noise. Compared to physical torture, so-called "no touch" torture c=
ould be considered more humane, but it is no less effective.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Like the infamous pillar, sound torture has a long history =E2=
=80=94 let's say we know an Aztec form of torture called the death whistle.=
</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">The CIA playlist often contains singles such as Enter Sandman'=
s Metallica, the hit Rage Against the Machine - Killing in the Name of or e=
ven Deicide, and their unforgettable F*ck Your God. What about the most pop=
ular song in Guantanamo? - "I love you" by Barney.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">In the school of survival in difficult conditions continuously=
 sound "Steps" by Rudyard Kipling.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Sergeant mark Hadsell of Psychological operations States that =
if a person has never listened to heavy metal, he is not able to sustain th=
e day and night with this music =E2=80=94 "the brain and the body begin to =
lose their functions. The thought slows down and the will is broken."</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Drug manipulation</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Manipulation with drugs, the US state Department, torture, Uni=
ted States, CIA</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Drug use, especially hallucinogens, was often used in psycholo=
gical torture. In the infamous program called Project MK-ULTRA, the CIA exp=
erimented with controlling mental activity. These experiments contained dru=
gs to " weaken the will of the individual through control of mental operati=
ons."</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">MK means that the project was organized for CIA technical serv=
ices, while "Ultra" is usually used to refer to secret intelligence data fr=
om the second world war.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">The most common drug is LSD, although the Agency has also expe=
rimented with the development of truth sera. The CIA's own website gives a =
report on the types of drugs used to establish the truth: different serums,=
 including scopolamine and various barbiturates.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">- There is no such magical means as in the movies. Barbiturate=
s, by reducing defense mechanisms, can sometimes be useful in interrogation=
, but even in the best cases they will cause illusions, fantasies, distorte=
d speech, etc.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Fake death.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Fake the death of the US state Department, torture, United Sta=
tes, CIA</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Remember how the great Russian writer Fyodor Dostoevsky descri=
bed his experiences when he was waiting for the death penalty, at the last =
moment was replaced by a link? This experience changed his whole life...</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Until now, this type of psychological impact is considered one=
 of the most effective and widely used in practice in various countries. Fr=
om staging the shooting and hanging to partial "strangulation" or "drowning=
".</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Another form is "waiting" for death-being on the so-called "de=
ath penalty list". To say that the consequences are irreversible inmates ar=
e suicidal, or have become a different kind of mania.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Extreme temperature</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Extreme temperatures us state Department, torture, us, CIA</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">The use of extreme temperatures is one of the "enhanced interr=
ogation" options used by the CIA and the FBI. Despite the fact that this to=
rture includes physical impact, it is considered psychological because it h=
as a mental impact.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Temperature reduction is also used for sleep deprivation. Howe=
ver, hypothermia is a common side effect, this form of torture has a high m=
ortality rate - up to 50%. Lowering the temperature could affect the memory=
 of the prisoners are suffering from amnesia. Using extremely high temperat=
ures can lead to thermal shock. Even if the necessary conditions are met, h=
eat stroke is usually fatal, so this form of torture can no longer be regar=
ded as psychological.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Fear</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Fear of us state Department, torture, us, CIA</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">The use of fears and phobias of prisoners can be effective, bu=
t not always feasible. The placement of arachnophobes in the same cell with=
 spiders is one of the forms of such torture. It involves a deep knowledge =
of the victim, so it is unlikely to be used in the "official" setting.</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Military psychologists questioned detainees in Guantanamo to u=
nderstand which of the phobias were used: the phobias of nudity, the phobia=
s of enclosed space, the phobias of darkness...</p>
<p class=3D"qtext_para" style=3D"margin:1em 0; display:inline-block; margin=
-bottom:1em">Tactile deprivation</p>
